GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF NORTH CAROLINA
SESSION 2025
H 1
HOUSE BILL 496
Short Title: Patriotic Youth Group Access. (Public)
Sponsors: Representatives Ross, Bell, Tyson, and Ward (Primary Sponsors).
For a complete list of sponsors, refer to the North Carolina General Assembly web site.
Referred to: Education - K-12, if favorable, Rules, Calendar, and Operations of the House
March 25, 2025
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ALLOW CIVIC YOUTH GROUPS TO GIVE PRESENTATIONS ABOUT
3 ORGANIZATION MEMBERSHIP TO STUDENTS IN PUBLIC SCHOOLS.
4 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
5 SECTION 1. G.S. 115C-206 reads as rewritten:
6 "§ 115C-206. State Board of Education; duties; responsibilities.
7 The Superintendent of Public Instruction shall prepare and present to the State Board of
8 Education recommendations for general guidelines for encouraging increased community
9 involvement in the public schools and use of public school facilities. These recommendations
10 shall include, but shall not be limited to provisions for:
11 …
12 (4) Local boards of education are to be directed to give priority in the use of
13 school facilities to Requiring public school units to permit any youth group
14 listed in Title 36 of the United States Code as a patriotic society, such as the
15 Boy Scouts of America, and its affiliated North Carolina groups and councils,
16 and the Girl Scouts of the United States of America, and its affiliated North
17 Carolina groups and councils, in order to encourage schools to facilitate access
18 for students to participate in activities provided by these groups at times other
19 than instructional time during the school day for the purposes of encouraging
20 civic education.the opportunity to give a presentation on the purpose of the
21 group, how to become a member of the group, and encouraging civic
22 education. Presentations given pursuant to this subdivision shall not exceed
23 10 minutes and shall be scheduled between the start and release times of the
24 instructional day. Presentation time does not count toward any instructional
25 hour requirements. Nothing in this section, or a policy or rule adopted
26 pursuant to this section, shall be construed as requiring a public school unit to
27 provide equal access to an organization that is not designated as a patriotic
28 organization.
29 …."
30 SECTION 2.(a) G.S. 115C-150.12C(28) reads as rewritten:
31 "(28) Access for youth groups. – Schools for the deaf and blind are encouraged to
32 facilitate access for students to participate in activities provided by any youth
33 group listed in Title 36 of the United States Code as a patriotic society, such
34 as the Boy Scouts of America, and its affiliated North Carolina groups and
35 councils, and the Girl Scouts of the United States of America, and its affiliated
*H496-v-1*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 North Carolina groups and councils. Student participation in any activities
2 offered by these organizations shall not interfere with instructional time
3 during the school day for the purposes of encouraging civic education.shall
4 develop policies to ensure that patriotic youth groups have access to schools
5 in accordance with the provisions of G.S. 115C-206(4)."
6 SECTION 2.(b) G.S. 115C-207 reads as rewritten:
7 "§ 115C-207. Authority and responsibility of local boards of education.
8 Every local board of education that uses State funds to implement programs under this Article
9 shall:
10 …
11 (4) Give priority in the use of school facilities to any youth group listed in Title
12 36 of the United States Code as a patriotic society, such as the Boy Scouts of
13 America, and its affiliated North Carolina groups and councils, and the Girl
14 Scouts of the United States of America, and its affiliated North Carolina
15 groups and councils, in order to encourage schools to facilitate access for
16 students to participate in activities provided by these groups at times other
17 than instructional time during the school day for the purposes of encouraging
18 civic education. If the local board of education denies priority access to a
19 patriotic society listed in Title 36 of the United States Code, the local board
20 shall provide reasons for the denial in writing to the requesting entity.Develop
21 policies to ensure that patriotic youth groups have access to schools in
22 accordance with the provisions of G.S. 115C-206(4).
23 …."
24 SECTION 2.(c) G.S. 115C-218.75(f) reads as rewritten:
25 "(f) Access for Youth Groups. – Charter schools are encouraged to facilitate access for
26 students to participate in activities provided by any youth group listed in Title 36 of the United
27 States Code as a patriotic society, such as the Boy Scouts of America, and its affiliated North
28 Carolina groups and councils, and the Girl Scouts of the United States of America, and its
29 affiliated North Carolina groups and councils. Student participation in any activities offered by
30 these organizations shall not interfere with instructional time during the school day for the
31 purposes of encouraging civic education.Charter schools shall develop policies to ensure that
32 patriotic youth groups have access to schools in accordance with the provisions of
33 G.S. 115C-206(4)."
34 SECTION 2.(d) G.S. 115C-238.66(13) reads as rewritten:
35 "(13) Access for youth groups. – Regional schools are encouraged to facilitate
36 access for students to participate in activities provided by any youth group
37 listed in Title 36 of the United States Code as a patriotic society, such as the
38 Boy Scouts of America, and its affiliated North Carolina groups and councils,
39 and the Girl Scouts of the United States of America, and its affiliated North
40 Carolina groups and councils. Student participation in any activities offered
41 by these organizations shall not interfere with instructional time during the
42 school day for the purposes of encouraging civic education.Regional schools
43 shall develop policies to ensure that patriotic youth groups have access to
44 schools in accordance with the provisions of G.S. 115C-206(4)."
45 SECTION 3. This act is effective when it becomes law and applies beginning with
46 the 2025-2026 school year.
